                <p>Key statutory provisions for Xero users in India:</p><ul><li><strong>CGST Act 2017, Section 9:</strong> GST levy on supply of goods and services; Xero configured with CGST/SGST/IGST rates per Act. <a href="https://cbic.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CBIC Portal</a></li><li><strong>CGST Act 2017, Section 37/39:</strong> GSTR-1 and GSTR-3B filing obligations; managed through CA-prepared data export from Xero since no native portal integration exists</li><li><strong>E-Invoicing Mandate:</strong> Mandatory for AATO above Rs 5 crore; Xero lacks native IRP - Patron manages through add-ons or manual workflow</li><li><strong>Income Tax Act 1961, Section 194C/194J:</strong> TDS on vendor payments tracked through dedicated Xero accounts; Form 26Q filed quarterly. <a href="https://www.incometax.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Income Tax Portal</a></li><li><strong>IGST Act 2017, Section 2(6):</strong> Export of services zero-rated under LUT; Xero configured with zero-rated export tax code; FIRC/BRC reconciliation managed</li><li><strong>Companies Act 2013, Section 128:</strong> Books of accounts maintained in Xero accessible in India; Xero cloud storage compliant with electronic records provisions</li></ul>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

